{"text": "\"Do not take life too seriously. You will never get out of it alive.\" Set at a point between Borderlands and Borderlands 2, four aspiring Vault Hunters fight alongside Handsome Jack, witnessing his transformation into the ruthless tyrant people loved to hate in Borderlands 2, and inadvertently assisting with the rise of the Hyperion Corporation and his position within it. My rating system consists of six categories in descending order of importance: - Atmosphere  - Characters  - Details  - Tactical demand  - Story  - Combat & Controls Based on the performance each category will receive one of the following grading: - S-Rank: excellent  - A-Rank: very good  - B-Rank: solid  - C-Rank: satisfactory  - D-Rank: inferior In case of an S-Rank rating, a game reference will be included in brackets as a token of my respect. Atmosphere: S-Rank (You make me so proud, minion. The way you're carrying on my fight against Sentinel and 5H4D0W-TP. It brings a tear to my eye. A figurative one, of course. The saline content of actual tears would rust my eye quicker than you could say 'tetanus shotâ€™.) Characters: S-Rank (When Claptrap speaks, I feel my brain cells committing suicide one by one.) Details: S-Rank (Did I mention I donâ€™t have a medical license?) Tactical demand: S-Rank (If it took more than one shot, you weren't using a Jakobs!) Story: S-Rank (With the Sentinel defeated, Jack enters the Vault and greets the Vault Hunters, but finds no item of value, other than a mysterious symbol floating midair. As he attempts to interact with it, the symbol then shows Jack a vision of the Warrior awakening. However, the vision is interrupted by Lilith, who phasewalks in front of him and punches through the Vault symbol, burning it onto Jack's face. She then disappears, leaving Jack behind with the Vault Hunters. Jack, having gone insane from the vision as well as Lilith's attack, swears vengeance on her, and all the \"bandits\" on Pandora. Realizing that the hero who once saved her on Helios is no more, Athena leaves Jack's employ.) Combat & Controls: S-Rank (1337 H4XZ00R!) To conquer all achievements of Borderlands: The Pre-Sequel, you will most likely spend more than 100 hours. You have to play the single-player campaign several times, due to challenges like â€˜That Helped, Right?â€™ and â€˜Executionerâ€™. â€˜Challengerâ€™ is a typical grind achievement. â€˜The Duelistâ€™, â€˜Mouth To Mouthâ€™ and â€˜Who you gonna call?â€™ are the only multiplayer achievement and quite simple to obtain. â€˜The Bigger They Areâ€™ will take the most time, because it requires a character around level 50 or higher. The achievements of the two DLCs are straight forward and easy enough to get with a high level character. Achievement difficulty: 9 of 10 Common:  - Singleplayer [+2]  - Multiplayer [+1] Special:  - Challenger [+1]  - The Bigger They Are [+1]  - Executioner [+1]  - That Helped, Right? [+1]  - DLCs [+2] Estimated time for 100 % completion: +100 hours Chronology: Borderlands: The Pre-Sequel (PC) First-person shooter game (Science-Fiction) â€“ 2014 Borderlands 2 (PC) First-person shooter game (Science-Fiction) â€“ 2012 Borderlands (PC) First-person shooter game (Science-Fiction) â€“ 2009", "appid": "261640", "steamid": "profiles/76561197960393131", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "19", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1471521600.0}
